<!--
<!DOCTYPE section SYSTEM "file:/opt/share/xml/Oxygen/docbook/dtd/docbookx.dtd">
--><ns2301:section xmlns:ns2301="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.introduction.coreFeatures">

  <ns2302:title xmlns:ns2302="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Some Core Features</ns2302:title>
  <ns2303:para xmlns:ns2303="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Besides being an open-source Unix-based operating system, Linux has the following features:
    <ns2304:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2304="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns2305:listitem xmlns:ns2305="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2306:para xmlns:ns2306="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
         The <ns2307:emphasis xmlns:ns2307="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Linux kernel is very configurable and compact,</ns2307:emphasis> ranging from 
         about 300kB to 1.5MB, depending on the configuration, with the average being about 600KB. 
         This makes Linux suitable for a wide range of platforms.
      </ns2306:para></ns2305:listitem>
      <ns2308:listitem xmlns:ns2308="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2309:para xmlns:ns2309="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
         Linux supports a very wide range of file systems -- more than any other operating system.
      </ns2309:para></ns2308:listitem>
      <ns2310:listitem xmlns:ns2310="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2311:para xmlns:ns2311="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        The Linux kernel can be easily recompiled, adding or removing or modifying kernel features.
      </ns2311:para></ns2310:listitem>
      <ns2312:listitem xmlns:ns2312="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2313:para xmlns:ns2313="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        The kernel is extended through modules which can be loaded and unloaded without
        bringing down the system.
      </ns2313:para></ns2312:listitem>
      <ns2314:listitem xmlns:ns2314="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2315:para xmlns:ns2315="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        The system dependency is largely localized to within the kernel. Hence, if Linux is ported
        to another platform, it is largely only the kernel which needs to be ported.
      </ns2315:para></ns2314:listitem>
      <ns2316:listitem xmlns:ns2316="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2317:para xmlns:ns2317="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux has been designed from the start as a multi-user operating system
        with support for disk-space quotas on a per user and per group basis.
      </ns2317:para></ns2316:listitem>
      <ns2318:listitem xmlns:ns2318="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2319:para xmlns:ns2319="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux is fast and efficient.  
      </ns2319:para></ns2318:listitem>
      <ns2320:listitem xmlns:ns2320="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2321:para xmlns:ns2321="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux uses preemptive multi-tasking.
      </ns2321:para></ns2320:listitem>
      <ns2322:listitem xmlns:ns2322="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2323:para xmlns:ns2323="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux supports virtual memory,<ns2324:abbrev xmlns:ns2324="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">i.e.</ns2324:abbrev> the physical memory is extended
        through swap space on hard disk(s).
      </ns2323:para></ns2322:listitem>
      <ns2325:listitem xmlns:ns2325="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2326:para xmlns:ns2326="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux is very stable.
      </ns2326:para></ns2325:listitem>
      <ns2327:listitem xmlns:ns2327="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2328:para xmlns:ns2328="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux uses the Unix security model which is known to be very solid.
      </ns2328:para></ns2327:listitem>
    </ns2304:itemizedlist>
  </ns2303:para>
</ns2301:section>